<hr />
<p>Simplistically we could use <code>atan(y/x)</code>.  <code>atan2(y,x)</code> does have advantages with <code>x</code> or <code>y</code> as infinity or some zero.</p>
<p>We do get slightly better numeric answers with <code>atan2(y,x)</code>,  instead of <code>atan(y/x)</code>, yet <code>atan(y/x)</code> remains an attractive simplification.</p>

Q: spring-boot-starter-amqp dependency cause CglibAopProxy throws AmqpException while calling CachingConnectionFactory.createConnection() A: <p>It is indeed possible that you have lazy init and since the listeners (I assume they are beans in your system) are not invoked by anything in the system they never go up.</p>
<p>Dropping lazy init can be counter productive. Instead, there is a brute-force option, mark all your listeners with <code>@Lazy(false)</code></p>
<p>A better approach would involve writing a custom loader.</p>
<p>First you need to mark all those listeners as not lazy via Bean Post processor. It's simpler than it sounds:</p>
<pre><code>@Slf4j
@Configuration
public class RabbitListenersEagerInitConfig implements BeanFactoryPostProcessor {

  @Override
  public void postProcessBeanFactory(ConfigurableListableBeanFactory beanFactory)
      throws BeansException {
    for (String beanName : beanFactory.getBeanDefinitionNames()) {
      BeanDefinition beanDefinition = beanFactory.getBeanDefinition(beanName);

      // Don't override explicit non-lazy config
      if (!beanDefinition.isLazyInit()) {
        continue;
      }

      Class&lt;?&gt; beanType = beanFactory.getType(beanName, false);
      if (beanType == null) {
        continue;
      }

      boolean hasRabbitListenerMethod = false;
      for (var method : beanType.getDeclaredMethods()) {
        if (AnnotatedElementUtils.hasAnnotation(method, RabbitListener.class)) {
          hasRabbitListenerMethod = true;
          break;
        }
      }

      if (hasRabbitListenerMethod) {
        beanDefinition.setLazyInit(false);
        log.info(&quot;Forcing eager init for RabbitListener bean: {}&quot;, beanName);
      }
    }
  }
}
</code></pre>
<p>After you need to make sure that your registry up and running, you can use either Smart Lifecycle or just Smart Initializer:</p>
<pre><code>@Slf4j
@Component
@RequiredArgsConstructor
public class RabbitListenersAutoStarter implements SmartInitializingSingleton {

  private final Collection&lt;RabbitListenerEndpointRegistry&gt; registries;

  @Override
  public void afterSingletonsInstantiated() {
    long overallStart = System.nanoTime();
    log.info(
        &quot;Starting all RabbitListenerEndpointRegistry instances (forcing listener initialization)&quot;);

    for (RabbitListenerEndpointRegistry registry : registries) {
      long registryStart = System.nanoTime();
      try {
        registry.start();
        long registryDurationMs = (System.nanoTime() - registryStart) / 1_000_000;

        log.info(
            &quot;Started RabbitListenerEndpointRegistry: {} with {} listeners in {} ms&quot;,
            registry,
            registry.getListenerContainers().size(),
            registryDurationMs);
      } catch (Exception e) {
        long registryDurationMs = (System.nanoTime() - registryStart) / 1_000_000;
        log.warn(
            &quot;Failed to start RabbitListenerEndpointRegistry {} after {} ms&quot;,
            registry,
            registryDurationMs,
            e);
        throw e;
      }
    }

    long overallDurationMs = (System.nanoTime() - overallStart) / 1_000_000;
    log.info(
        &quot;Finished starting all RabbitListenerEndpointRegistry instances in {} ms&quot;,
        overallDurationMs);
  }
}
</code></pre>
<p>You should see logs on startup to check that all your listeners are up and running.</p>

Q: Is there a way to directly convert CSV to Parquet with DuckDB in Java? A: <p>As jqurious pointed out the correct syntax is indeed:</p>
<pre class="lang-sql prettyprint-override"><code>COPY (FROM read_csv(&quot;INPUTFILE&quot;, delim=';')) TO &quot;OUTPUTFILE&quot; (FORMAT parquet)
</code></pre>
<p>When implementing this in my application this resulted in out of memory errors, which I could fix by changing it to the following:</p>
<pre class="lang-sql prettyprint-override"><code>PRAGMA memory_limit='16GB';
COPY (FROM read_csv(&quot;%s&quot;, delim=';')) TO &quot;%s&quot; (FORMAT parquet);
CHECKPOINT;
VACUUM;
</code></pre>
<p>However, this is actually a little <em>slower</em> (370s vs 347s) then using the same method when creating a table and then exporting that to a parquet file.</p>
<p>The final solution I came to then was this:</p>
<pre class="lang-sql prettyprint-override"><code>PRAGMA memory_limit='16GB';
CREATE TABLE &quot;%s&quot; AS
SELECT * FROM read_csv(&quot;%s&quot;, delim=';');
COPY &quot;%s&quot; TO &quot;%s&quot; (FORMAT parquet);
CHECKPOINT;
VACUUM;
</code></pre>

Q: Is there any way to add divider or separator in PrimeNG P-dropdown value set A: <p>The existing solutions don't seem ideal since knowing the current item isn't necessarily enough info to know if a divider should be added at that particular item.</p>
<p>The best solution I've found is to make use of grouped options.</p>
<p>Create some options like this (<code>divider</code> is arbitrary; see the template further down):</p>
<pre class="lang-js prettyprint-override"><code>const groupedOptions = [
  {
    items: [
      { label: 'An Option', value: 1 },
      { label: 'Another Option', value: 2 }
    ],
  },
  {
    divider: true,
    items: [
      { label: 'A Third Option', value: 3 },
      { label: 'A Fourth Option', value: 4 }
    ],
  }
];
</code></pre>
<p>And then create a dropdown similar to this:</p>
<pre class="lang-html prettyprint-override"><code>&lt;p-dropdown
    [options]=&quot;groupedOptions&quot;
    optionLabel=&quot;label&quot;
    optionValue=&quot;value&quot;
&gt;
    &lt;ng-template pTemplate=&quot;group&quot; let-group&gt;
        &lt;p-divider
            *ngIf=&quot;group.divider&quot;
        /&gt;
    &lt;/ng-template&gt;
&lt;/p-dropdown&gt;
</code></pre>
<p>The main issue with this is grouping and <code>p-divider</code> add a ridiculous amount of extra padding, so these classes ended up being necessary:</p>
<pre class="lang-scss prettyprint-override"><code>p-dropdown .non-padded-groups .p-dropdown-item-group {
    margin: 0;
    padding: 0;
    background: none;
}

p-divider .non-padded-divider {
    margin: 0;
    padding: 0;
}
</code></pre>
<p>Then, those classes can be added to the <code>styleClass</code> of each element.</p>

Q: How do I use Uri.parse() method while testing? A: <p>You can run your tests with this so it can mock uri parsing.<br />
For more info check <a href="https://developer.android.com/training/testing/local-tests/robolectric" rel="nofollow noreferrer">here</a></p>
<pre class="lang-kotlin prettyprint-override"><code>@RunWith(RobolectricTestRunner::class)
@Test
    fun testStringToUri_validString_returnsUri() {

        val expectedUri = Uri.parse(&quot;content://media/external/audio/media/42&quot;)    // Line 165
        val actualUri = converter.stringToUri(&quot;content://media/external/audio/media/42&quot;)

        assertEquals(expectedUri, actualUri)
    }
</code></pre>

Q: Negative narrowing of union type with TypeIs of TypeVar not working as expected in new mypy version A: <p>As suggested by commenter <a href="https://stackoverflow.com/users/14401160/sterliakov">STerliakov</a>, and discussed in <a href="https://github.com/python/mypy/issues/20330" rel="nofollow noreferrer">this github issue</a>, this seems to be a bug in mypy, introduced in version 1.18.1.</p>
<p>Until this is fixed in mypy, add <code># type: ignore[return-value]</code></p>
<pre class="lang-py prettyprint-override"><code>_T = TypeVar('_T')


def mypy_fails(x: _T | int, checker: Callable[[Any], TypeIs[_T]], default: int) -&gt; int:
    if checker(x):
        return default
    else:
        return x  # type: ignore[return-value]
</code></pre>
